{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 09:18:24.844559", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnostic report — Clos (fat-tree) EBGP lab\nDate: (current state snapshot)\n\nExecutive summary\n- The control plane (FRR/EBGP) across the routers is converged: all routers have BGP routes for the two leaf subnets (10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24) and inter-router /31 links are up. Spines and super-spine have expected next-hops to reach each leaf prefix.\n- The only clear anomaly is at the host layer: pc_0_1 is not running/unreachable (container not running). This makes host-to-host traffic between pc_0_0 and pc_0_1 impossible despite correct routing in the router fabric.\n- Conclusion (root cause): pc_0_1 host failure (container stopped) — host-level outage. Network infrastructure (router interfaces, BGP advertisements, routes) appears operational.\n\nObserved symptoms and evidence\n- pc_0_1 is not reachable / container not running:\n  - Attempts to run commands on pc_0_1 returned Docker/container errors: \"container ... is not running\" (seen when collecting ifconfig / ip addr / ip route and in ping attempts). This directly shows the host is down.\n- pc_0_0 interface and routing:\n  - pc_0_0 has IP 10.0.0.2/24 and default route via 10.0.0.1 (leaf_router_0_0). (ip addr / ip route present)\n  - Ifconfig shows no packets on pc_0_0 (RX/TX 0) — consistent with idle host and no successful traffic to pc_0_1.\n- Leaf routers:\n  - leaf_router_0_0:\n    - Interfaces: eth2 10.0.0.1/24 (host-facing), eth0 172.16.0.5/31 (to spine_0_0), eth1 172.16.0.9/31 (to spine_0_1) — all UP.\n    - FRR config: router bgp 65200 with network 10.0.0.0/24 advertised.\n    - Routing table: C>* 10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected; B>* 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.4 (spine_router_0_0).\n  - leaf_router_0_1:\n    - Interfaces: eth2 10.0.1.1/24 (host-facing), eth0 172.16.0.7/31, eth1 172.16.0.11/31 — all UP.\n    - FRR config: router bgp 65201 with network 10.0.1.0/24 advertised.\n    - Routing table: C>* 10.0.1.0/24 is directly connected; B>* 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.6 (spine_router_0_0).\n- Spine routers:\n  - spine_router_0_0:\n    - Interfaces: eth1 172.16.0.4/31 (to leaf_0_0), eth2 172.16.0.6/31 (to leaf_0_1), eth0 172.16.0.1/31 (to super-spine) — all UP.\n    - FRR config: router bgp 65100, neighbors including super-spine (172.16.0.0) and leaves.\n    - Routing table: B>* 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.5; B>* 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.7.\n  - spine_router_0_1:\n    - Interfaces: eth1 172.16.0.8/31, eth2 172.16.0.10/31, eth0 172.16.0.3/31 (to super-spine) — all UP.\n    - FRR config: router bgp 65101, neighbors including super-spine and leaves.\n    - Routing table: B>* 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.9; B>* 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.11.\n- Super-spine router:\n  - super_spine_router_0:\n    - Interfaces eth0 172.16.0.0/31 (to spine_0_0), eth1 172.16.0.2/31 (to spine_0_1) — UP.\n    - FRR config: router bgp 65000 with neighbors to both spines.\n    - Routing table: B>* 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.3 (spine_0_1); B>* 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.3.\n- BGP presence:\n  - Each router's running config and route table show that the leaf networks 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 are present in BGP and installed in RIBs across the fabric. No missing BGP routes observed in the sampled routing outputs.\n\nDevice-by-device status (concise)\n- pc_0_0: interface present, IP 10.0.0.2/24, default route to leaf_router_0_0. Host appears up but idle (no traffic). Ping to pc_0_1 could not be completed (pc_0_1 down).\n- pc_0_1: host/container not running — unreachable. Commands failed with container-not-running error.\n- leaf_router_0_0: interfaces UP, BGP configured and advertising 10.0.0.0/24, route table present.\n- leaf_router_0_1: interfaces UP, BGP configured and advertising 10.0.1.0/24, route table present.\n- spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1: interfaces UP, BGP peers to super-spine and leaves configured, have routes to both host subnets.\n- super_spine_router_0: interfaces UP, BGP neighbors to spines configured, receives both leaf prefixes.\n\nAnomalies identified\n1. Host outage: pc_0_1 container not running — prevents host-layer connectivity for 10.0.1.0/24 end-host. This is the primary and only operational anomaly observed.\n2. Low/no traffic counters on host-facing interfaces:\n   - Both leaf_router eth2 interfaces show TX/RX 0 packets toward hosts (leaf_router_0_0 and leaf_router_0_1 host-facing interfaces show zero traffic); this is consistent with pc_0_1 being down and pc_0_0 idle. Not necessarily an anomaly in the fabric, but indicates host-level inactivity.\n3. No evidence of control-plane or link failures in the router fabric:\n   - All inter-router /31 interfaces are up (addresses assigned and show in ip addr).\n   - BGP routes for both leaf prefixes are present across spines and super-spine.\n   - FRR configs show correct neighbor ASes and networks.\n\nRoot cause determination\n- The immediate root cause of the observed host-to-host connectivity failure (pc_0_0 <-> pc_0_1) is a host-level outage: pc_0_1 is not running (container stopped). Router control plane and forwarding plane are functioning and have routes for both subnets; therefore the fabric is able to route if both hosts were present and responding.\n- There is no evidence from the gathered data of BGP or inter-router link failures; BGP appears converged and consistent with the topology.\n\nLimitations and notes about data collected\n- Active ping tests between hosts failed / could not complete because pc_0_1 was not running. A full end-to-end ping could not be executed.\n- I relied on FRR running configurations and routing tables and host net-config outputs captured in parallel. The routing/RIB snapshots indicate BGP advertisement/propagation is functioning.\n- If further confirmation is needed for control-plane details (BGP neighbor state, BGP session counters, or BGP update logs), we can gather \"show bgp summary\" / \"show bgp neighbors\" outputs from FRR on the routers — but current route tables already show the networks are installed.\n\nSummary (one-line)\n- Router fabric healthy and BGP-converged; the observed service outage is due to pc_0_1 (host/container) being down — root cause is host-level failure, not the network.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 12159, "output_tokens": 2933, "total_tokens": 15092, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 2816}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1088}}}
